<br>
If you are considering going to war with a country, there are 2 things you must consider.  First, you must consider whether you have the right to do so.  Second, if you decide you have the right to do so, you must decide whether you wish to do so and whether it is in your best interests.<br>
<br>
Ok, now for the first, whether you are justified.  There are numerous reasons why I believe we are justified in invading Iraq.  The invasion of Kuwait is sufficient justification for me to consider the war legal.  He does not respect the sovereign rights of another nation, I see no reason why we are required to respect his.  In the case of Iraq, we also have a UN resolution which authorizes whatever means are necessary (see Ayiar's post for the exact wording, I don't remember) to effect its enforcement.  Finally, his failure to destroy the WMD's in the presence of UN inspectors is sufficient in and of itself to bring the war withing our rights.<br>
<br>
Now, if you follow that logic, there are quite a few other nations that we are justified in invading.  I do believe this to be the case.  I believe we'd be perfectly justified in invading the Congo, North Korea, or Syria right about now (each for different reasons).<br>
<br>
The next question is whether we should invade a country.  This is where all of the reasons I listed come into play.  Essentially, at this phase of the decision making process, I believe that we are automatically legally justified in the invasion.  It is only a question of whether it's in our best interests.  The various reasons come into play here.  WMD's is one.  There does not have to be proof, we have already established guilt, now we are simply deciding on the best course of action.  Evidence of WMD's or terrorist links, a desire to free the Iraqi people, and a fear of future actions by Saddam are all factors at this point.  Again I stress that Saddam has no rights at this point for me in the decision making process.  Our decision to invade is entirely based on our own interests or if we choose, the interests of other concerned parties (the Iraqi people, surrounding nations, etc).  His actions have already made the war just.<br>
<br>
Now in the case of Iraq, I believe the combination of reasons made invasion in our best interests.  In the case of some of the other nations (Syria and North Korea), for various reasons, I do not believe invasion is in our best interests.  (I actually would support sending troops in to establish order in the Congo, but that's another story.)<br>
<br>
I hope this clarifies my viewpoint.<br>
<br>
