Currently, there is a desire by the majority of Iraqis to have the US out of their country.  Another desire is to bring the clerics into power.  The Iraqis are deeply conservative for the most part, they have pent-up religious fervour, and there lies a political vacuum due in part to Saddam Husseins’ oppression and the occupation of US/British forces.  For the majority of Iraqi society the only way to express their feelings is through religion.  The end-all results are thus devastating to the US.  If elections were held tomorrow, Islamists would rule the nation.<br>
<br>
The Bush administration is well aware of the Islamist threat.  If it came to fruition, all the careful planning that America has conducted will come to naught.  Instead of sowing the seeds of democracy a la American style, or enjoying the economic benefits of their oil, Washington will have to deal with a hostile regime in Baghdad that could very well lead or inspire other nations up the same path of governance.<br>
<br>
So the United States has begun countering this threat by making their own threats.  First, there were warnings to Iran not to interfere with Iraq’s internal affairs.  These threats and gestures were an attempt to limit Islamist sentiment.  But in reality the Islamic fervour gripping Iraq is indigenous in roots.  The majority of the country is Shi’ite ~70% (though Arabic Shi'ite as opposed to Persian).  To compound the situation further, Secretary of Defence Donald Rumsfield directed a warning to Iraqis saying “if you’re suggesting, how would we feel about an Iranian-type government with a few clerics running everything in the country, the answer is: That isn’t going to happen.”<br>
<br>
The meaning of Rumsfield’s statement is profound.  It, in effect denies the very democratic and freedom ideals espoused by George Bush all along.  The message seems to be simple enough – you can choose who rules your country, but only if your choice is pro-American and secular.<br>
<br>
Rumsfield is denying the possibility that democracy and Islam can coexist.  This is not the first time Western leaders have made this sort of democratic value judgment.  During the Cold War our enemy was the almighty communists.  Undemocratic leaders were openly tolerated as long as communism was off their shores.  After the Cold War and more importantly after September 11th the enemy d’jour is Islam.  All manner of tyrannical leaders and governments can be supported as long as Islamists are kept out of power.<br>
<br>
Algeria for example, after decades of brutal military rule held its first democratic elections in 1991.  When it became clear that the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) would take the parliament, the military decided to cancel the elections, ban the FIS, and started a horrendous campaign of suppression.  At the time George Bush Sr. applauded the acts of the Algerian government.  In Egypt, Hosni Mubarak has been leading the country for over twenty years, “winning” every election.  Quite an amazing record for a “democratic” country.  When one looks deeper into Egyptian politics it is quite manifest that the ruling part of Egypt crushes any political opposition.  Mubaraks’ government receives the second most aid after Israel (which also openly abuses state suppression).  In Saudia Arabia there have NEVER been any democratic elections.  Fifteen of nineteen September 11th hijackers were Saudis, yet the US loves Saudia Arabia.  There are no calls for democracy from the US or 10 Downing Street.<br>
<br>
The problem is a double standard – democracy but only pro-US democracy.  The United States will not have free elections in Iraq until it can properly implement their agenda.  America will delay elections as long as possible, citing security concerns and stability of the nation.  This will only further cause greater degradations within Iraq.  Subverting or denying a proper democracy in Iraq will not stop the popular Islamic ideals from eventually taking over, whether via peaceful means or hostile intents.  I personally, do not believe in a theocratic state, and believe strongly that religion has no part in governance.  It is not my will though to decide for the Iraqis what is right or wrong, but up to them.  Like every other political ideology – socialism, communism, free-market capitalistic libertarianism, the Islam code as a political entity has to be given a chance to prove itself or not as per the will of the people.  That is democracy.<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
 <p>Sage Neibruoma Meztress<br>
65 Enchanter<br>
