Neibruoma, you list communism, theocracy, and several other possible government types as branches of democracy.  They are not.  Democracy implies an ongoing ability of the people to change their leadership through peaceful means.  If a muslim theocracy were created as in Iran, people would have no such power.  Thus that would not be a democracy.<br>
<br>
Anywon, members of the UN were authorized to enforce the resolutions by all necessary means.  Just because they don't specifically establish no-fly zones does not mean that they do not authorize them.  The Constitution does not authorize speeding tickets, but most of us would accept them as valid.  Second, the Bush used WMD's to make the case for the war to the American people and to explain to them why he thought the war should be fought.  However, the Bush administration always used UN resolutions as the grounds for the war being legal.  They repeatedly said they did not need a 2nd UN resolution and that existing resolutions were sufficiently inclusive.  They did want one for some of their allies as it would help politically, but it was in no way necessary.  Even if the Bush administration did support something that was the right decision for the wrong reasons, I would still support the action.  As long as the action is right, I don't care what reasoning people use to get to it.  I will go through some resolutions and dig stuff up for you.<br>
